CMake is a mature utility for building software projects.
CMake works by generating Makefiles for the host
machine from platform and compiler independent
configuration files that describe the build process,
rather than script it.

A CMake configuration file, called CMakeLists.txt, describes the recipe for building a component of the software. This description includes compiler options (e.g. defaulting REAL to an 8-byte wide type), compiler definitions (e.g. defining BPCH_DIAG for binary punch format diagnostics), the files to compile, and a list of dependencies. The CMake engine reads these configuration files, solves the dependencies, and then generates a Makefile structure for compiling the project.

This work is PR #35 on the GEOS-Chem GitHub page (https://github.com/geoschem/geos-chem/pull/35). Once it is merged, you will be able to build GEOS-Chem Classic and GCHP with CMake! The existing Makefile-based build system is not going to be removed, nor will any compiler compatibility or software dependencies change. Once this work is merged, I will actively support related questions and issues. Please don’t hesitate to submit issues on GitHub or contact me directly!
Contact me at

A priority of the GCHP Working Group is improving the accessibility of GCHP by making it easier to use. Currently, one barrier to using GCHP is compiling—particularly for first-time users. Building GCHP is significantly more complicated than GEOS-Chem Classic because of the new dependencies introduced by GCHP. The GEOS-Chem Classic repository contains 365 Fortran files. The GCHP repository contains more than 3000 Fortran, C, and C++ files. The sheer volume of code in GCHP means that maintaining the GCHP build system takes considerable effort.

This work aims to simplify the process of compiling GEOS-Chem Classic and GCHP for users, and reduce the burden of maintaining the build system for developers, by using the popular utility CMake. This development implements the necessary files so that GEOS-Chem Classic and GCHP can be built with CMake. This work is PR #35 on the GEOS-Chem GitHub page.

The flow of the Makefile-based GCHP build is illustrated below. Each component’s Makefile calls the Makefiles of all its dependencies. These relationships can be difficult to maintain for third-party subcomponents with complex build configurations like MAPL.

With the CMake-based build system, each component’s CMakeLists.txt describes to the CMake engine how it is built and its dependencies. Then, the CMake engine generates the Makefile structure for compiling GCHP.
